We went to Woodie’s night during the Wing Out series and were very impressed! The guy who seemed to be in charge (owner, manager?) came to each and every table to explain the process of how they make their wings - double deep fried in a butter/buffalo sauce and lightly smoked so they are fresh and crispy. He said times have been hard recently and they’ve been trying to reinvent themselves, including introducing all these fun new wing flavors such as cheesy garlic, siracha soy, sweet bourbon bacon, Nashville hot, and of course regular or mild buffalo. You can get two different sauces per single order so you can try out different flavors. Dog owners can bring their dogs out on the patio where the friendly waitstaff will bring them a treat. Great vibe at this place, would definitely come back!

A group of about 10 of us came to Woodie’s this past Saturday to watch the OSU vs. Penn State game. A couple of my buddies ordered the tall self serve beer tap for themselves. Another couple of guys ordered as well but they had a different tab. Well, I guess the bar was low on the self serve taps because when their tap appeared to be the lowest level compared to everyone else at the bar we had servers and bussers coming up to them asking if they would hurry up and finish so they could take it to another table. I am not even kidding 3 or 4 different people came up to them in 8 minutes to get them to rush and drink their beer. To the point where my friends had to verbally express they did not want to rush and one of the staff ignored them and physically took their glasses and filled them to the top in an effort to rush them. THIS HAPPENED TWICE where staff took their glasses and topped them off to the rim. Would a server cut up someone else’s steak so they could take their steak knife to another table? Would a bartender rush someone to finish a cocktail because they needed the glass for another patron? Would a server pour a hot bowl of soup down someone’s throat because they needed bowls for another table? I’d like to note they were drinking it at a normal pace already and it is not like they had it on the table for an hour.  I have never seen anything like this in an establishment and it was very uncomfortable.. I’d also like to note I’m a 20 something super understanding chick in the hospitality industry who never writes negative reviews but the staff here crossed a line. You cannot force people to rush and finish their alcoholic beverages because someone at another table ordered a container that the bar is low on.

We went there last night after a Second City show. We were probably one of the last tables to order food, being that it was 10:30 at the time (kitchen closes at 11:00), but we did call ahead and sort of warned them we were coming. I feel our waitress must have been tired, although she did get us everything we needed, she never once cracked a smile, nor looked happy to be there. I am also I server, so I get it, late at night the guests who walk in right before the kitchen is closing can be a bit annoying. Still, all I would ask is that she smile a little. I still think this was a timing issue on our part. That being said, the food was phenomenal! I got the Chicago Dip burger, and it was cooked to my specifications, and was absolutely delicious. My husband got the bison burger which he also loved. My siblings and sister in law, were also all very impressed by the food. A little note though, we were sitting upstairs at the far leftside corner table right under the skylight, and during our meal my sister and sister in law were getting dripped on by a leak in the skylight somewhere, so you may want to check that out.

Overall: With a great atmosphere, specials, and food, Woodie's is a step above the rest in the Old Town area.  The good: Every time I've been here the food has hit the spot. It's high-brow pub fare, but in a good way. They have tons of burgers, sandwiches, apps, etc. to choose from, and they're all tasty. The fried chicken sandwich I got was juicy, filling, and bacon-y. Plus, sweet potato fries, enough said. The service every time has been friendly, and the atmosphere is effectively small and homey.  The not-so-good: Music can get pretty loud if you're just coming for food/hanging out, but obviously good if you're getting plastered. Prices are just a tad high for the food. Small space gets cramped pretty quickly.  Atmosphere:8/10 Service: 8.5/10 Food: 9/10

She then said the membership costs $5 and we get the $10 discount when we come back next time. She then refused to take the charge off. I was astonished that they were so brazen in this kind of deceptive selling tactic. Why would they mislead people like that and expect them to come back?
